How Next.js sends HTML to the browser in pieces instead of one giant blob — and why that single idea can transform your app’s perceived performance.
Streaming Server-Side Rendering (Streaming SSR) lets a Next.js server start sending HTML to the browser before the entire page has finished rendering. Instead of the user staring at a blank screen while the server waits on a slow database query or third-party API, they see the page shell and fast content almost instantly, while slower sections “pop in” as their data becomes ready. This post explains the theory from first principles, walks through production-ready code, and includes hand-drawn (ASCII) diagrams so you can visualize exactly what’s happening on the wire — no external images, just text you can read anywhere.

1. Introduction
If you’ve built anything with Next.js in the last couple of years, you’ve probably heard the term “streaming” thrown around alongside React Server Components, Suspense, and the App Router. For beginners, this can feel like a wall of buzzwords. This article strips that away and builds the concept up piece by piece:

• What problem streaming actually solves

• How it works mechanically (HTTP, React internals)

• How to implement it in a real Next.js App Router project

• What changes when you take it to production
By the end, you should be able to explain streaming SSR to a teammate on a whiteboard, and also ship it confidently in a real app.

2. A Quick Primer: SSR, CSR, and Hydration
Before streaming makes sense, let’s align on vocabulary.

• Client-Side Rendering (CSR): The server sends a nearly empty HTML file plus a big JavaScript bundle. The browser downloads the JS, runs it, fetches data, and then paints the UI. Fast servers, slow first paint.

• Server-Side Rendering (SSR): The server does the work of rendering React components into HTML before sending anything to the browser. The browser gets a fully-formed page to paint immediately, then “hydrates” it (attaches event listeners, makes it interactive).

• Hydration: The process where React takes the static HTML that was rendered on the server and “wakes it up” in the browser, matching it against the React component tree so clicks, inputs, and state start working.
Traditional SSR already sounds great — so what’s the catch?

3. The Problem: Why Traditional (Non-Streaming) SSR Falls Short
In classic SSR, the server has to finish rendering the entire page — every component, every data fetch — before it can send any bytes back to the browser. If one component needs a slow API call (say, a recommendations engine that takes 3 seconds), the whole page waits on it, even if the rest of the page was ready in 100ms.
Traditional (Blocking) SSR — Timeline View
--------------------------------------------------------------
Client Server
| |
|------------ HTTP Request -------------->|
| | fetch(header data) 100ms
| | fetch(product data) 300ms
| | fetch(reviews) 3000ms <-- bottleneck
| | render ALL components
| | (nothing sent yet)
| |
|<---------- Full HTML (3.4s) ------------| <- single big blob
| |
| Browser paints everything at once |
| Hydrate entire tree |
--------------------------------------------------------------
Total time to first pixel on screen: ~3.4 secondsThis is often called the “slowest component wins” problem. Users end up staring at a white screen for as long as the slowest piece of data takes to load — even though most of the page was ready in a fraction of that time.

4. What Is Streaming SSR?
Streaming SSR flips this model. The server renders and sends HTML incrementally, as soon as each piece is ready, using chunked HTTP responses. The browser doesn’t wait for one big response — it receives and paints multiple smaller chunks over time.
Streaming SSR — Timeline View
--------------------------------------------------------------
Client Server
| |
|------------ HTTP Request -------------->|
| | render shell + fast parts (100ms)
|<----- Chunk 1: Shell + Header ----------|
| Paint immediately (100ms) |
| | fetch(product data) done (300ms)
|<----- Chunk 2: Product Section ---------|
| Insert into DOM, hydrate this part |
| | fetch(reviews) still running...
| | reviews ready (3000ms)
|<----- Chunk 3: Reviews Section ---------|
| Insert into DOM, hydrate this part |
| |
|<---------- Stream closed ---------------|
--------------------------------------------------------------
Time to first pixel: ~100ms (34x faster than blocking SSR!)
Time to fully interactive: still ~3s, but perceived speed is transformedNotice: the total time for everything to be ready hasn’t changed much. What changed is when the user starts seeing and using the page. This is the core value proposition of streaming — it optimizes for perceived performance and Core Web Vitals like Time to First Byte (TTFB) and First Contentful Paint (FCP), without you needing to make your slow API magically fast.

5. The Engine Behind It: React 18 and Suspense
Streaming SSR in Next.js is built on top of two React 18 features:
5.1 renderToPipeableStream / renderToReadableStream
Under the hood, React’s server renderer doesn’t produce one HTML string anymore — it produces a stream. Next.js’s App Router uses this internally, but it’s worth seeing the raw React API once so the concept “clicks.” This is not how you’d write Next.js code day-to-day, but understanding it demystifies everything above:
// conceptual-server.js
// A simplified illustration of React's underlying streaming API.
// Next.js does something equivalent to this internally for you.import { renderToPipeableStream } from 'react-dom/server';
import App from './App';
function handleRequest(req, res) {
const { pipe } = renderToPipeableStream(<App />, {
// Fires once the "shell" (non-Suspense-wrapped content) is ready
onShellReady() {
res.statusCode = 200;
res.setHeader('Content-Type', 'text/html');
pipe(res); // start streaming bytes to the client NOW
},
// Fires only if the initial shell itself errors out
onShellError(error) {
res.statusCode = 500;
res.send('<h1>Something went wrong</h1>');
},
// Fires once EVERY suspended component has resolved
onAllReady() {
// Useful for crawlers/bots that need the full page (see SEO section)
},
onError(error) {
console.error(error);
},
});
}
The key mental model: React renders the tree, and whenever it hits a component wrapped in <Suspense> that isn't ready yet (because it's await-ing data), React doesn't block — it emits a fallback placeholder in that spot, keeps rendering the rest of the page, and comes back to fill in the real content later via a small inline <script> chunk that swaps the placeholder out once the data resolves.
5.2 Selective Hydration
A neat side effect: React also hydrates progressively. If a user clicks a button inside a section that has already streamed in — even if other sections are still loading — React prioritizes hydrating and responding to that interaction first. You get an app that’s responsive in parts, rather than all-or-nothing.

6. Streaming SSR in Next.js’s App Router
Next.js (App Router, app/ directory) wires all of the above together automatically. As a developer, you mostly work with two primitives:

• async Server Components — components that can await data directly in their function body.

• <Suspense> boundaries — you draw the lines around which parts of the page are allowed to "arrive later."
6.1 A Basic Example
Imagine a product page with two sections: a fast product summary, and a slow reviews widget.
// app/products/[id]/page.tsx
import { Suspense } from 'react';
import ProductSummary from './ProductSummary';
import Reviews from './Reviews';
import ReviewsSkeleton from './ReviewsSkeleton';export default function ProductPage() {
return (
<main>
{/* Renders fast - included in the initial shell */}
<ProductSummary />
{/* Slow section - streamed in independently once ready */}
<Suspense fallback={<ReviewsSkeleton />}>
<Reviews />
</Suspense>
</main>
);
}
// app/products/[id]/ProductSummary.tsx
async function getProduct() {
const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/products/123', {
next: { revalidate: 60 }, // cache for 60s (ISR-style)
});
return res.json();
}export default async function ProductSummary() {
const product = await getProduct();
return (
<section>
<h1>{product.name}</h1>
<p>${product.price}</p>
</section>
);
}
// app/products/[id]/Reviews.tsx
async function getReviews() {
// Simulating a slow third-party API
const res = await fetch('https://api.example.com/reviews/123', {
cache: 'no-store', // always fresh, never cached
});
return res.json();
}export default async function Reviews() {
const reviews = await getReviews();
return (
<section>
<h2>Customer Reviews</h2>
<ul>
{reviews.map((r: { id: string; comment: string }) => (
<li key={r.id}>{r.comment}</li>
))}
</ul>
</section>
);
}
// app/products/[id]/ReviewsSkeleton.tsx
export default function ReviewsSkeleton() {
return (
<section aria-busy="true">
<h2>Customer Reviews</h2>
<div className="skeleton-line" />
<div className="skeleton-line" />
<div className="skeleton-line" />
</section>
);
}What happens here, step by step:

• Next.js starts rendering ProductPage.

• ProductSummary awaits its fetch (fast, cached) and resolves quickly — it's part of the initial HTML shell.

• Reviews is wrapped in <Suspense>. Because its await hasn't resolved yet, React immediately renders ReviewsSkeleton in its place and ships the shell now, without waiting for reviews.

• When the reviews fetch finally resolves, Next.js streams a small extra chunk of HTML + a tiny inline script that replaces the skeleton with real content — no client-side re-fetch needed, no flash of a spinner-then-refetch, it's all part of the same server response.
6.2 The loading.tsx Convention (Automatic Streaming)
Next.js gives you a file-based shortcut so you don’t even need to hand-write <Suspense> at the page level. Any loading.tsx file automatically wraps its sibling page.tsx in a Suspense boundary:
// app/products/[id]/loading.tsx
export default function Loading() {
return <p>Loading product…</p>;
}File-system → Suspense boundary mapping
--------------------------------------------------
app/products/[id]/
├── page.tsx <-- the async component being streamed
└── loading.tsx <-- becomes the <Suspense fallback={...}>
--------------------------------------------------
Next.js compiles this into (conceptually):<Suspense fallback={<Loading />}>
<Page />
</Suspense>
This is great for whole-route loading states but coarser than manually placed <Suspense> boundaries — it treats the entire page as one streaming unit. For granular streaming (some sections fast, some slow), nest your own <Suspense> boundaries inside page.tsx, as shown in section 6.1.
6.3 Nested Boundaries: Controlling Granularity
You can nest boundaries as deeply as you want. Each boundary is an independent “stream lane” — slow content in one boundary never blocks a sibling boundary.
// app/dashboard/page.tsx
import { Suspense } from 'react';export default function Dashboard() {
return (
<div className="grid">
<Suspense fallback={<CardSkeleton />}>
<RevenueCard /> {/* resolves in ~200ms */}
</Suspense>
<Suspense fallback={<CardSkeleton />}>
<ActiveUsersCard /> {/* resolves in ~400ms */}
</Suspense>
<Suspense fallback={<CardSkeleton />}>
<SlowAnalyticsCard /> {/* resolves in ~4000ms */}
</Suspense>
</div>
);
}
Streaming lanes for the Dashboard page
------------------------------------------------------------
t=0ms shell + all 3 skeletons sent immediately
t=200ms RevenueCard chunk streamed in -> lane 1 done
t=400ms ActiveUsersCard chunk streamed in -> lane 2 done
t=4000ms SlowAnalyticsCard chunk streamed in -> lane 3 done
------------------------------------------------------------
Each lane is independent — a slow lane never blocks a fast one.This is the real power of streaming: you decide, section by section, what’s allowed to be “eventually consistent” on first load.

